visualization tools make it accessible not only to elite clubs but also to amateur and
semi-professional teams seeking to incorporate data and video analytics into training
planning [15].
● Other Systems and Applications: In addition to the examples above, many innovative
wearable devices contribute to the adaptive training ecosystem. The WHOOP wristband,
for example, tracks internal load parameters such as heart rate, heart rate variability
(HRV), and sleep quality throughout the day [1]. It analyzes this data using cloud-based
AI to provide a recovery score and personalized daily training recommendations.
Athletes receive color-coded feedback—such as “green” (ready) or “red” (fatigued)—and
can adjust their training accordingly [1]. Similarly, Intel’s 3D Athlete Tracking (3DAT)
system uses cameras and AI to analyze movement in three dimensions in real time. It
captures data on running technique, stride length, and joint angles to help improve
technical form. In football specifically, devices like Playermaker, which attach to the
ankle, collect detailed technical data such as number of ball touches, use of both feet,
and step symmetry. Using AI, the device then recommends drills to improve technique
[15]. In the endurance sports domain, apps like TrainAsONE and Xert offer continuously
adaptive training plans for amateur runners and cyclists, demonstrating how the concept
of AI-driven training is becoming widespread across all levels [15].
In summary, both academic research and commercial products have established the practical
viability of AI-assisted training. Teams are able to monitor training data in real time with
STATSports and Catapult, integrate tactical and technical insights using Metrica, and take
proactive steps to protect player health with tools like Zone7. This multifaceted ecosystem has
elevated professional training planning to a more scientific, data-driven, and personalized level.
V. INTEGRATING WEEKLY TRAINING PLANS WITH REAL-TIME
FEEDBACK
In football, a microcycle (typically a week-long training plan) involves pre-planning the
distribution of physical loads and rest days throughout the week. However, real-time data
collected from players may necessitate fine-tuning of this plan. The key to integration lies in
establishing a balanced interaction between long-term planning and short-term feedback. In
other words, while weekly goals and periodization provide a framework, the player’s day-to-day
condition and training responses allow for adjustments within that framework [13].
In practice, integration works as follows: at the start of the week, coaches prepare a weekly
training load schedule based on the match calendar (e.g., strength training on Monday, high-
intensity training on Tuesday, active recovery on Wednesday, etc.). This plan follows scientific
periodization principles and aims to have players in peak condition by the weekend [13]. For
example, as match day approaches, training intensity typically tapers down, while midweek
sessions may include higher loads to maintain fitness. As the week progresses, GPS and
biometric data collected from players continuously monitor how well the plan is being followed.
Suppose Wednesday’s data indicates that a key player is more fatigued than expected, has had
poor sleep, or hasn’t fully recovered from the previous session—an adaptive system could use
this information to lighten Thursday’s training session. This prevents overexertion and better
prepares the player for the weekend match.
Adaptive algorithms aim to align such micro-level changes with the broader macro plan. For
instance, in a study by Connor et al., an AI-driven feedback system monitored daily training
loads within a 12-week program and automatically adjusted future session intensities if there
were deviations from target goals [5]. Even when unexpected events occurred (such as injury,
illness, or early termination of training), the system was able to re-optimize the remaining
sessions to stay on course with the overall training objectives. Results showed that this
approach significantly reduced deviations from the planned workload compared to traditional
methods [5]. Essentially, the system adheres to the goal of achieving the “total weekly training
load” while making necessary daily adjustments.
Another important approach is integrating scientific metrics such as the Acute:Chronic
Workload Ratio (A:C). Weekly planning must ensure that a player’s acute (1-week) training load
remains within a safe range relative to their chronic (4-week) load average. Feedback systems
calculate this ratio in real time to verify whether the training is progressing as planned. If a
player’s A:C ratio exceeds the upper threshold of 1.5 (indicating the past week’s load is much
higher than usual), the system may suggest reducing the workload for the rest of the week [13].
Conversely, if the load is below target, it may recommend additional individual sessions. This
ensures that periodization principles are upheld with adjustments informed by real-time data.
Today, some AI-driven platforms automate this integration process. For example, Xert, an app
used in running and cycling, offers a continuously adaptive training schedule instead of a fixed
program. Its Adaptive Training Advisor evaluates the athlete’s condition after each session and
updates the next day’s session accordingly. As a result, scenarios like “I couldn’t follow today’s
plan” or “I feel great today, what should I do?” are predicted and accommodated within the
system. Such platforms make feedback integration user-friendly and accessible, even for
amateur athletes. At the professional level, this integration is usually overseen by performance
scientists and coaches. AI systems generate recommendations, and humans make the final
decision [10]. For example, if an AI system reports, “Player X completed 20% less high-speed
running today than planned; consider adding sprint drills tomorrow,” the coach then considers
the match schedule and the player’s subjective condition before acting on the suggestion.
In summary, combining a weekly plan with real-time data feedback has become a modern
necessity in sports science. Static plans are becoming obsolete, giving way to dynamic,
predictive strategies. While the weekly program provides a roadmap, real-time feedback
systems continuously fine-tune that path, keeping the athlete on the safest and most efficient
trajectory [10]. This approach ensures that both the big picture (season goals, match
performance) and the daily details (fatigue, motivation) are managed simultaneously.
VI.PROPOSED TECHNICAL ARCHITECTURE AND COMPONENTS
To implement such an adaptive training system, a multi-layered technical architecture must be
designed. In general, this architecture consists of the following components: data collection
layer, analysis and processing layer, recommendation engine, and user interface:
● Data Collection Layer:
This bottom layer gathers data from all sensors and devices worn by the player. These
may include GPS vests, accelerometers, gyroscopes, heart rate monitors, sleep trackers,
and possibly ball or ankle-mounted sensors used during training. The raw data from
these devices (e.g., position coordinates per second, heart rate counts, step counts) is
transmitted wirelessly to cloud servers either in real time or at the end of the training
session. For example, the STATSports Apex device can stream data via Bluetooth or
ANT+ to a receiver on the sidelines, while a wearable like WHOOP syncs data
continuously to the cloud throughout the day [12]. What matters most at this layer is the
synchronized and compatible collection of data from different sources and its secure
storage [12]. All data is stored in a data warehouse or a time-series database.
● Analysis & Data Processing Module:
At the middle layer, raw data is transformed into meaningful insights. The first step
involves cleaning and synchronizing the data (e.g., aligning GPS and heart rate data by
timestamp, filtering missing or erroneous entries). Then, business intelligence and data
analytics processes are applied to extract derived features from the raw data. Key
performance metrics such as total running distance, high-speed distance, number of
sprints, average heart rate, heart rate variability during training, and RPE (Rate of
Perceived Exertion) are calculated. In the STATSports system, such metrics, including
total distance, high-speed running (HSR), and dynamic stress load (DSL) [13], are
automatically generated and reported. Within this module, the core AI algorithms
operate. Machine learning models process the incoming data to make predictions and
assessments:
○ An injury risk model can generate a risk score based on recent training loads and
recovery trends.
○ A performance prediction model can estimate a player’s readiness for match day
based on current training data.
○ An anomaly detection system can flag unusual fatigue or performance drops.
● These analyses may run in real time or after each training session. For instance, the
system may assess whether a player has progressed or regressed compared to the
previous day, using machine learning algorithms to benchmark the results. This module
supports the decision-making process by generating insights using the machine learning
techniques outlined in Section 3. In complex, multi-source architectures, AI-based
interpretation—as highlighted in the TTMS study—can reveal intricate patterns that
human analysts might miss. The analysis module is also responsible for comparing
calculated metrics and model outputs to predefined thresholds (e.g., calculating the
Acute:Chronic Workload Ratio) [1].
● Recommendation Engine (Decision Support System):
The insights from the analysis module are translated into actionable training
suggestions. This layer houses rule-based logic and optimization algorithms. For
example, if the injury risk model shows an 80% risk for a player, the recommendation
engine might suggest “Assign rest day tomorrow.” Or, if a player’s high-intensity running
distance over the past three days is below the plan, the system may recommend “Add
extra interval training.”
The recommendation engine also takes the coach’s predefined goals and constraints
into account. For instance, if Friday is intended to be a light session, the system will not
suggest adding extra load that day. This engine operates using a blend of business rules
(if-then logic) and trained models. In advanced systems, this module may even be driven
by a reinforcement learning agent that learns over time which recommendations yield
the best results. However, in practical settings, the system typically provides a shortlist
of recommendations.
● User Interface (UI) and Feedback:
At the top of the architecture is the interface through which coaches, performance staff,
and possibly players interact with the system. This interface may be a web-based
dashboard, a mobile app, or a specialized tablet application. It visually presents
information from lower layers through charts, tables, alerts, and recommendation lists.
For instance, the UI might highlight in red that a player has reached 90% of their running
distance goal but only 50% of their high-speed running target, with a note such as “high-
speed workload low.” This allows coaches to instantly grasp the situation. Through the
interface, the coach can approve or modify system suggestions. For example, if the
system suggests a rest day but the coach wants to schedule a light technical session
instead, this can be manually adjusted—and the system will learn from it.
A well-designed UI consolidates the weekly schedule, daily adjustments, and player
status reports into one view, simplifying the decision-making process. A separate sub-
interface may also be provided for players to track their own metrics and receive
personalized feedback (e.g., “You exceeded your running goal today” or “Your heart rate
was within normal limits”).
In implementing this architecture, several technical considerations are essential:
● Real-time capability: The system must process data with minimal latency.
● Scalability: It should handle data streams from the entire team without performance
issues.
● Reliability and security: Data loss must be prevented, and sensitive health information
must be protected.
● Integration: The system must be compatible with different devices and data formats.
Most modern systems are cloud-based, meaning data is processed and stored on internet
servers. However, as seen in newer STATSports devices, on-device AI (edge computing) is
becoming a trend. This allows real-time analysis directly on the device—particularly useful for
instant feedback during training—without needing to transmit data to the cloud first [12]. Still, a
centralized database and analysis platform remain indispensable for long-term data
management and complex modeling.
Lastly, for this architecture to succeed, it must operate in continuous collaboration with the
technical staff. Recommendations and alerts generated by the system must be filtered through
human expertise. While the architecture offers automation, the role of the human coach is
vital—to interpret insights, define goals, and make final decisions. AI assists, but human
judgment remains central.
VII. CONSIDERING THE SPECIFIC NEEDS OF DIFFERENT
FOOTBALL POSITIONS
When designing adaptive training systems, it is essential to recognize that players in different
football positions have distinct physical and technical demands. A goalkeeper’s workload
profile differs greatly from that of a midfielder, and their training focuses and risks also vary. An
AI-assisted system can account for these positional differences in several ways:
● Goalkeepers:
Goalkeepers typically cover much less distance during matches but perform more
explosive actions (e.g., quick dives, jumps for crosses). According to one study, a
goalkeeper runs about 5.5 km on a match day, performs only 50–100 meters of
sprinting, and executes 5–10 high-intensity accelerations or decelerations. These values
are significantly lower than those of a midfielder. Therefore, an adaptive system should
apply different workload thresholds for goalkeepers. Instead of tracking running
distance, it could monitor reaction times, jump height, and kicking range. If a goalkeeper
completes a high number of explosive actions (e.g., 15+ dives) in a session, the system
might suggest rest or low-intensity technical training the next day. Due to the nature of
their role, goalkeepers also require upper body strength and flexibility [16]. The adaptive
program should periodically emphasize exercises that develop these attributes, such as
plyometrics and mobility training. Since goalkeepers may remain stationary for long
periods and then need to react explosively, mental focus drills and active recovery
techniques may also be integrated.
● Defenders:
Defenders can be further divided into center-backs and full-backs. Center-backs perform
short, explosive movements (e.g., tracking strikers, sudden changes in direction), while
full-backs tend to cover more distance with up-and-down runs along the flanks. Overall,
defenders cover a moderate-to-high total distance (~9–11 km per match, with full-backs
on the higher end). Adaptive systems should closely monitor acceleration and sudden
speed changes for defenders, especially center-backs, since timing and quickness are
critical. If a center-back’s number of high-intensity accelerations falls below target, the
system may recommend additional speed drills. For full-backs, endurance and speed are
key, so the system should track their high-speed running distance. Strength training is
also vital for defenders due to frequent physical duels; adaptive plans may incorporate
more resistance training for defenders compared to other positions. For instance, two
weightlifting sessions per week might be standard for a defender, while only one may
suffice for an attacker. An AI-based system can analyze a defender’s in-game stats (e.g.,
aerial duels won, tackle success) and, if performance drops in those areas, increase the
strength training volume accordingly.
● Midfielders:
Midfielders are typically the players who cover the most distance and have the highest
aerobic and repeated sprint demands. Elite-level midfielders may run 11–13 km per
match, much of it at moderate intensity, interspersed with sprints. Adaptive systems
must pay special attention to recovery capacity for midfielders, as they are often the
most fatigued during congested match schedules. For example, if a midfielder’s morning
heart rate variability (HRV) is lower than usual (a sign of fatigue), the system may reduce
training load for the day. Midfielders also require a broad range of skills, since they
contribute to both defensive and offensive phases. An adaptive program should aim to
develop speed, endurance, and agility in a balanced manner. While analyzing midfielder
data, the system might not prioritize maximum speed as much as for attackers but
rather focus on total load and intensity distribution. Nevertheless, if a midfielder’s high-
speed running distance is consistently low, the system may interpret it as a lack of
explosive speed and recommend targeted sprint training. Since passing accuracy is also
crucial for midfielders, the system could optimize technical sessions accordingly—for
instance, planning additional passing drills if a midfielder’s pass completion rate drops
in matches.
● Forwards and Wingers:
Attacking players (forwards and offensive wingers) may run slightly less than
midfielders overall, but they perform the highest number of high-speed efforts. A forward
may cover 9–11 km per match, with key actions involving explosive sprints for scoring
chances or pressing. Adaptive systems should track metrics such as number of sprints,
maximum speed, and explosive power. If a winger’s top speed during training is below
their known potential, the system may recommend more speed work. For forwards,
shooting frequency and accuracy are also important indicators; some systems can even
track shot efficiency (e.g., percentage of accurate shots). If a forward hasn’t had enough
scoring opportunities in recent games and sprint metrics are down, the system may
interpret this as a physical issue (e.g., lack of freshness or sharpness) and reduce
training load to allow for recovery. Agility and quick changes of direction are also vital
for these players; systems can monitor 5–10 meter acceleration data or zigzag run tests
to assess form. Position-specific settings may lead the adaptive algorithm to assign
more speed and agility drills to attackers, while defenders may receive relatively less
long-distance running.
Adaptive systems can also incorporate positional differences during the modeling phase.
Machine learning models can treat position as an input feature. For example, an injury
prediction model might use different thresholds for goalkeepers than for midfielders. Likewise,
rule-based thresholds can be tailored to position—for instance, a rule like “If a goalkeeper
exceeds 20 km of running in a week, issue a warning” would be irrelevant for midfielders but
critical for goalkeepers. Research has shown that the relationship between external training
load and physical characteristics of players depends heavily on their tactical role (i.e., position).
This underscores the importance of position-specific approaches in adaptive systems [17]. For
example, a tall, powerful center-back and a short, fast winger differ not only in their match roles
but also in their training requirements; a well-designed system can recognize and accommodate
these differences.
In conclusion, adaptive training systems must function with distinct parameters and objectives
tailored to goalkeepers, defenders, midfielders, and forwards. The universal aim across all
positions is to maximize performance and minimize injury risk, but the path to achieving this
must be position-specific. Sharpening a goalkeeper’s reflexes, increasing a defender’s
endurance and strength, maintaining a midfielder’s aerobic capacity, and enhancing a forward’s
explosive speed and finishing—these can all be achieved within the same system via separate
modules and configurations. A well-structured AI-powered training platform will treat positional
differences as a personalization layer, ensuring each player receives the most suitable workload
according to their role. In turn, this enables every part of the team to perform at its best—raising
the overall level of team performance to its highest potential.
